1. Introduction

1.1 Overview

MaiaKoda is a dual-nature programming language ecosystem consisting of two integrated languages:

Language Type Purpose
Maia Compiled systems language OS kernels, drivers, embedded systems, performance-critical code
Koda Interpreted scripting language Embedded scripting, standalone shell, build automation, web development

1.2 Design Philosophy

1. Safety First - Multi-layer safety (borrow checking, reference capabilities, compile-time RC)
2. No Garbage Collection - Deterministic performance, explicit memory management
3. Zero-Cost Abstractions - No runtime overhead for language features
4. Pascal Syntax - Clean, readable, no significant whitespace
5. No Macros - No code obfuscation, comptime functions instead
6. Self-Contained - No LLVM dependency, native backends for x86_64, ARM64, RISC-V, WASM
7. TOML Configuration - All configurations use TOML format
8. Markdown Documentation - All documentation uses GitHub Markdown

1.3 Language Relationship

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                         MaiaKoda                                  │
├─────────────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────┤
│           Maia              │              Koda                  │
│  (Compiled Systems Lang)    │    (Interpreted Scripting Lang)    │
├─────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────┤
│ • No GC                     │ • Embedded (Lua-style)             │
│ • Compile-time RC           │ • Standalone shell (Bash-style)    │
│ • Borrow checker            │ • Async/await                      │
│ • Reference capabilities    │ • Native templates                 │
│ • Explicit allocators       │ • Built-in VCS                     │
│ • Inline assembly           │ • Built-in ORM                     │
│ • 4 backends (x86/ARM/RV/WASM)│ • Web framework (first-class)    │
│ • FFI to 7 languages        │ • FFI via Maia                     │
└─────────────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────┘
```

